  "doc_id": "21134",
  "text": "However, the type of required reasoning is not always purely logical (true or false, 1 or 0) but can also be probabilistic (the degree of certainty or probability that an event will happen, represented by a value between 0 and 1). Bayesian networks (BNs) have been chosen by many previous researchers as models for managing probabilistic reasoning in ontologies [CITATION_1] . This is because in addition to its ability to perform probabilistic reasoning with prior knowledge, a BN has a graphical structure like that supported by ontological representation in OWL.",
